<DOC><DOCNO> AP880229-0289 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1444EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Canada-Strike     02-29 0190</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Canada-Strike,0198</SECOND><HEAD>More Than 5,000 Workers Strike Northern Telecom</HEAD><DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   More than 5,000 Northern Telecom Ltd. productionand office workers went on strike in five Canadian cities Mondayafter the union rejected a last-minute economic proposal from thecompany.   ``We are quite a ways apart on some very basic issues,'' saidBob White, president of the Canadian Auto Workers union.   White said the company wants to cut cost-of-living allowances by35 percent and has failed to meet the union's proposal for indexedpensions. The union is also seeking higher wages and a sweetenedbenefit package. Wages now are $15 to $18 an hour.   The contract expired Sunday at midnight and the strike beganafter a deadline of Monday at 11 a.m. EST.   Affected by the strike are a repair facility in Saint John, NewBrunswick, and manufacturing plants in Ontario at Bramalea,Belleville, London and Kingston that make wire, cable, telephonesand office telecommunications equipment.   The company is 52.3 per cent owned by conglomerate BCE, formerlyBell Canada Enterprises, and has 24 plants and repair operations.Fourteen of the company's plants are located in the United States.</TEXT></DOC>